[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    194[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;180;142;173m*[38;2;180;142;173m"Cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring uses the institutional cohort registry as the source of truth for cohort axes (no ad-hoc enumeration in code). Recipe-specific cohort axes: name-tradition cohort (Spanish double-surname, East Asian family-name-first, Arabic patronymic, names-with-diacritics, English-default; the dominant driver of cohort disparity in name-change handling); transgender-or-gender-diverse cohort, populated only from patient-consented self-identification (never from inferred or third-party-asserted classification; the bucketed-cohort-label discipline from Finding S4 applies with extra force); name-change-frequency cohort (zero, one, two-to-three, four-or-more); age-of-name-change cohort (under-25, 25-45, 45-65, over-65). Metrics: (a) per-cohort name-change detection rate (computed weekly); (b) per-cohort name-change false-acceptance rate (sampled audit, computed weekly); (c) per-cohort review-queue aging (computed weekly); (d) per-cohort time-to-resolve (computed weekly); (e) per-cohort sampled error rate (false-merge or false-split, computed monthly). Disparity calculation: absolute difference between the cohort with the highest rate and the cohort with the lowest rate, computed per-metric per-cycle. Alarm thresholds: detection-rate disparity > 0.05 = MEDIUM; review-queue-aging disparity > 0.05 = MEDIUM; time-to-resolve disparity > 0.10 = MEDIUM; false-acceptance-rate disparity > 0.01 = HIGH (clinical safety implications); any disparity > 2x the threshold = HIGH. Alarms route to the analytics governance committee, the equity-monitoring committee, the patient-experience-and-dignity committee (which has explicit dignity-stakes-relevant oversight authority for this recipe), and (per-driver) the clinical-informatics committee for reference-data-driven cohorts and the patient-portal-flow team for registration-and-portal-driven cohorts, with a 5-business-day SLA for the first investigation report. The post-mortem and any remediation (per-cohort threshold tuning, per-tradition reference-data gap analysis, registration-flow data-capture improvements, patient-portal-flow improvements for the name-change-frequency and age-of-name-change cohorts) is documented in the cohort-disparity ledger and reviewed quarterly by the longitudinal-matching steering committee with patient-experience-and-dignity-committee co-chair. The dignity-stakes-disparity translation is explicit: cohort-disparity metrics in this recipe measure how disparately one cohort's patients experience friction in the registration, clinical-record-rendering, and release-of-information workflows; remediation prioritizes patient-experience improvement, not just analytics-accuracy improvement."[38;2;180;142;173m*[K
